        "heading": "How the Pieces Interact",
        "content": "### Reciprocal Deposits + Analytics = The Core Loop\nThe deposit network generates real-time data on flows, composition, and risk. The analytics layer turns that data into actionable intelligence for ALCOs. Better analytics → better decisions → more deposits placed through the network → more data → better analytics. This is the **data flywheel** that incumbents like IntraFi don't have (their legacy systems produce batch reports, not real-time intelligence).\n\n### CUSO + Core Integrations = The Growth Engine\nCredit unions are the greenfield — zero incumbent. But CUs run on different cores than banks (Jack Henry Symitar is dominant for CUs). Getting the Symitar integration done unlocks the CUSO's addressable market dramatically. This is why the Series B earmarked funds for Jack Henry specifically.\n\n### Wholesale Funding + Analytics = The Expansion Play\nTerm Funding (brokered CDs) is a different product than reciprocal deposits, but it uses the same infrastructure: real-time pricing, network connectivity, digital order management. The analytics layer tells a bank \"you have a $50M liquidity gap maturing in 90 days\" — and the Term Funding product says \"here are the best rates to fill it.\" Problem identification + solution delivery in one platform.\n\n### The Institution-Owned Model = The Moat\nAcross all products, ModernFi's structural advantage is the same: **institutions own the network**. Banks share in NBID economics. Credit unions are CUSO member-owners. This creates retention and alignment that IntraFi's vendor model can't match — you don't churn from something you own."
